1
00:00:19,350 --> 00:00:21,310
[indistinct chatter on radio]

2
00:00:22,390 --> 00:00:23,980
[in Spanish]
Good morning.

3
00:00:24,650 --> 00:00:25,860
Good morning, Mom.

4
00:00:27,770 --> 00:00:30,210
- Your cat bit me again.
- You stole my pencils.

5
00:00:30,230 --> 00:00:32,840
- Why are you fighting?
- Because he stole my pencils!

6
00:00:32,860 --> 00:00:34,380
- She's making it up.
- Stop fighting.

7
00:00:34,410 --> 00:00:38,220
- Let's see.
- Let's go, sweetie. What time is it?

8
00:00:38,240 --> 00:00:41,100
- 6:40 a.m.
- God, I'm late again.

9
00:00:41,120 --> 00:00:43,960
Remember to ask your brother
what we talked about.

10
00:00:44,580 --> 00:00:48,190
- Tell him school starts next week.
- Yes. I'll ask him, all right?

11
00:00:48,210 --> 00:00:51,150
I still have to buy the books, everything.

12
00:00:51,170 --> 00:00:53,570
I told you I'll ask him, my love,
all right?

13
00:00:53,590 --> 00:00:58,410
And you still haven't tied your shoes.
So, like I taught you, right?

14
00:00:58,430 --> 00:01:01,910
We have the rabbit ear,
we go around the tree, and...?

15
00:01:01,930 --> 00:01:03,330
And it goes in the hole.

16
00:01:03,350 --> 00:01:05,190
[explosion thunders in distance]

17
00:01:07,730 --> 00:01:10,480
- [car alarms wailing]
- That was a loud one.

18
00:01:14,450 --> 00:01:18,620
[Steve] You threaten a man's family,
and you find out what he's made of.

19
00:01:19,580 --> 00:01:23,750
Pablo Escobar was made of rage,
revenge and terror.

20
00:01:25,790 --> 00:01:29,520
Unable to lash out directly
at his enemies in Cali,

21
00:01:29,540 --> 00:01:32,400
he went after their prized
legitimate business,

22
00:01:32,420 --> 00:01:36,840
one they couldn't hide:
their beloved chain of drugstores.

23
00:01:37,470 --> 00:01:42,450
And he blew them to shit along with anyone
unlucky enough to be standing nearby.

24
00:01:42,470 --> 00:01:45,060
We're talking dozens of bombs.

25
00:01:45,560 --> 00:01:50,500
He put the city of Bogotá on edge
and the Colombian government on notice.

26
00:01:50,520 --> 00:01:55,670
Continue to ignore Los Pepes, refuse to
acknowledge their crimes, and you're next.

27
00:01:55,690 --> 00:01:58,220
LUIS LONDOÑO WHITE, KIDNAPPER OF THOSE
SERVING PABLO ESCOBAR

28
00:01:58,240 --> 00:01:59,970
But terror brings more terror,

29
00:01:59,990 --> 00:02:03,680
and Los Pepes responded
with their own special brand.

30
00:02:03,700 --> 00:02:05,970
We came up with a name for their displays.

31
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:08,850
- [in Spanish] Sit him there.
- [Steve] Colombian folk art.

32
00:02:08,870 --> 00:02:10,190
[in Spanish]
Over here.

33
00:02:10,210 --> 00:02:13,130
[Steve]
Like I said, you can't make this shit up.

34
00:02:14,260 --> 00:02:18,740
The point of all this?
Psychopaths sending a message...

35
00:02:18,760 --> 00:02:19,900
[laughing]

36
00:02:19,930 --> 00:02:21,890
No matter how far you go...

37
00:02:22,560 --> 00:02:24,490
[in Spanish]
Look at that ugly son of a bitch.

38
00:02:24,520 --> 00:02:26,640
We'll take it one step further.

39
00:02:28,350 --> 00:02:30,790
The gates of hell were officially opened.

40
00:02:30,810 --> 00:02:33,920
One... two... and three.

41
00:02:33,940 --> 00:02:37,590
And everyone was scrambling
to get out of the fire.

42
00:02:37,610 --> 00:02:39,700
Or climb into it.

43
00:02:40,320 --> 00:02:43,370
[Latin guitar theme music plays]

44
00:04:09,870 --> 00:04:13,020
[Hermilda in Spanish] This family
is the only thing I care about.

45
00:04:13,040 --> 00:04:16,270
- You're the one that...
- [Tata] Me? Me, ma'am? Me?

46
00:04:16,290 --> 00:04:19,940
[Hermilda] We shouldn't leave, Tata.
[Tata] All of this is your fault.

47
00:04:19,960 --> 00:04:22,840
If you'd listened to Pablo,
my brother would still be alive.

48
00:04:24,260 --> 00:04:28,780
[Hermilda] Because you do that so well?
Do you listen to him?

49
00:04:28,810 --> 00:04:34,770
When you're always criticizing him,
doubting him, worrying.

50
00:04:36,650 --> 00:04:37,940
[whispers] Tata.

51
00:04:41,940 --> 00:04:43,090
[door closes]

52
00:04:43,110 --> 00:04:47,370
[Hermilda]
I would never put this family in danger.

53
00:04:48,410 --> 00:04:50,040
Tell her, Pablo.

54
00:04:50,620 --> 00:04:53,250
Tell her it's not my fault, Pablo.

55
00:04:54,790 --> 00:04:57,890
- [whispers] I know, Mom.
- This isn't my fault. Tell her, Pablo.

56
00:04:57,920 --> 00:05:02,460
It's not your fault. I know.
It's not your fault.

57
00:05:03,510 --> 00:05:05,360
[sobbing]

58
00:05:05,380 --> 00:05:07,430
Everything's all right, Mom.

59
00:05:08,760 --> 00:05:10,350
It wasn't your fault.

60
00:05:11,270 --> 00:05:13,640
[takes deep breath]

61
00:05:47,760 --> 00:05:50,350
[shaky exhale]

62
00:06:09,530 --> 00:06:11,200
[sighs]

63
00:06:16,790 --> 00:06:20,730
- [flies buzzing]
- [Judy] Look at these smiling faces.

64
00:06:20,750 --> 00:06:23,060
We didn't want to make you
uncomfortable, Judy.

65
00:06:23,090 --> 00:06:28,090
How considerate of you.
So that's why no one called me?

66
00:06:29,470 --> 00:06:32,350
Because this lab belongs to the Moncadas.
Mmm?

67
00:06:32,970 --> 00:06:36,790
So I was supposed to be notified
when it was taken back.

68
00:06:36,810 --> 00:06:40,940
- That wasn't made clear to us.
- I'm making it clear now, Carlos.

69
00:06:42,310 --> 00:06:45,920
- What are we going to do with that?
- All the cocaine is going to Cali.

70
00:06:45,940 --> 00:06:48,110
That is my cocaine.

71
00:06:48,780 --> 00:06:53,760
Look, Judy, we decided that not a single
kilo of cocaine will be moved in Medellín

72
00:06:53,780 --> 00:06:56,640
until Pablo Escobar is dead.

73
00:06:56,660 --> 00:07:00,100
That's our strategy. To asphyxiate him.

74
00:07:00,120 --> 00:07:04,060
That's the Cali cartel's strategy?

75
00:07:04,090 --> 00:07:06,690
To keep making money
while the rest of us go hungry?

76
00:07:06,710 --> 00:07:11,470
- You know we can't trust them.
- No. Not them or any of you.

77
00:07:12,390 --> 00:07:16,350
We don't trust any drug trafficker.

78
00:07:19,020 --> 00:07:23,730
Well, let's not get personal, Carlos.
All right?

79
00:07:24,400 --> 00:07:26,150
We all need friends.

80
00:07:36,410 --> 00:07:37,870
Sir, would you like some?

81
00:07:43,080 --> 00:07:45,210
[low chatter on radio]

82
00:07:49,170 --> 00:07:50,380
[gasps]

83
00:07:56,890 --> 00:07:58,850
Go, go, go, go, go!

84
00:08:01,640 --> 00:08:04,020
[broken radio chatter continues]

85
00:08:05,770 --> 00:08:06,940
[man] Sir?

86
00:08:11,450 --> 00:08:12,740
Are you all right?

87
00:08:38,890 --> 00:08:40,640
[people chatter indistinctly]

88
00:08:42,180 --> 00:08:43,850
- [gasps]
- Are you all right?

89
00:08:45,980 --> 00:08:47,230
[car honking]

90
00:08:56,030 --> 00:08:59,200
[siren approaching]

91
00:09:00,620 --> 00:09:03,120
[indistinct chatter]

92
00:09:11,050 --> 00:09:14,360
- [in Spanish] We're done working together.
- What's bothering you?

93
00:09:14,380 --> 00:09:18,220
The killing of innocent civilians,
for starters.

94
00:09:18,930 --> 00:09:22,410
Whether they're innocent or guilty,
I don't decide.

95
00:09:22,430 --> 00:09:24,180
That's what priests are for, no?

96
00:09:31,530 --> 00:09:35,150
The Castaños are crazier than ever,
and that wasn't part of the plan.

97
00:09:36,570 --> 00:09:38,240
But it's working.

98
00:09:39,200 --> 00:09:41,620
Not if I stop providing you intel.

99
00:09:43,040 --> 00:09:47,430
For what it's worth, I am on your side.

100
00:09:47,460 --> 00:09:49,390
I don't like what's happening.

101
00:09:49,420 --> 00:09:51,880
Medellín is my home
and I love it very much.

102
00:09:53,880 --> 00:09:56,090
As far as the methods
of the Castaños go...

103
00:09:57,090 --> 00:10:02,820
well, those are the methods
that have Pablo's people hiding like rats.

104
00:10:02,850 --> 00:10:06,620
Including that gonorrhea of a lawyer,
Fernando Duque.

105
00:10:06,640 --> 00:10:11,250
Our guys fired a whole fucking clip
at him, point blank.

106
00:10:11,270 --> 00:10:15,490
Can you believe that these sons of bitches
didn't hit him once?

107
00:10:16,110 --> 00:10:18,110
I need you to help me find him.

108
00:10:20,700 --> 00:10:23,720
He's Pablo's mouthpiece
and his connection to the government.

109
00:10:23,740 --> 00:10:27,720
What we want is to exterminate this rat.

110
00:10:27,750 --> 00:10:33,500
That way, we'll get to Pablo
and we can end this madness, Peña.

111
00:10:46,310 --> 00:10:47,540
[doorbell ringing]

112
00:10:47,560 --> 00:10:50,460
I've told you! You have to... [stammers]

113
00:10:50,480 --> 00:10:54,880
What are you doing?
You have to bring the passports.

114
00:10:54,900 --> 00:10:59,050
Juliana... they're trying to kill me.
We have to get out of here.

115
00:10:59,070 --> 00:11:02,030
I think you're the one
who needs to leave.

116
00:11:03,160 --> 00:11:05,930
[stammers]
Can I see Simon, at least?

117
00:11:05,950 --> 00:11:08,770
- Where... Simon!
- Stop, Fernando!

118
00:11:08,790 --> 00:11:10,710
Simon is at school.

119
00:11:11,830 --> 00:11:17,210
Besides, this isn't even your week.
So, please... leave.

120
00:11:24,600 --> 00:11:26,060
[door closes upstairs]

121
00:11:41,490 --> 00:11:42,530
[alarm disarms]

122
00:11:51,710 --> 00:11:53,350
[kids laughing, chattering]

123
00:11:53,380 --> 00:11:55,900
- Oh, what's going on?
- How are you?

124
00:11:55,920 --> 00:11:57,440
- Bye, Anda!
- Bye!

125
00:11:57,460 --> 00:12:00,340
Where's Mom? Why do you have her car?

126
00:12:01,130 --> 00:12:02,300
Get in.

127
00:12:05,220 --> 00:12:07,510
[chatter in Spanish over radio]

128
00:12:08,390 --> 00:12:09,410
[Javier knocks]

129
00:12:09,430 --> 00:12:12,080
[in English] Hey, I need you
to run a trace on this name.

130
00:12:12,100 --> 00:12:13,690
- Okay.
- Find this guy.

131
00:12:14,730 --> 00:12:16,570
All right? You look tired.

132
00:12:21,950 --> 00:12:22,990
[in Spanish]
Come in.

133
00:12:26,950 --> 00:12:28,740
Go on, son. Sit down.

134
00:12:30,620 --> 00:12:33,290
So, you're being reassigned...

135
00:12:34,330 --> 00:12:38,210
and you will be moved into the intel unit
that was formed a couple of months ago.

136
00:12:41,210 --> 00:12:42,840
You'll be all right there.

137
00:12:44,890 --> 00:12:47,260
You're sending me to an office
because I made a mistake?

138
00:12:50,520 --> 00:12:51,600
Anything else?

139
00:12:59,570 --> 00:13:01,070
Yes, sir, Colonel.

140
00:13:07,740 --> 00:13:11,120
[door opens, closes]

141
00:13:21,460 --> 00:13:23,130
How are you, Papa?

142
00:13:27,840 --> 00:13:29,360
And you?

143
00:13:29,390 --> 00:13:33,430
- How long will we be there?
- Not long.

144
00:13:34,940 --> 00:13:38,690
Just long enough for me
to get some things figured out here.

145
00:13:43,740 --> 00:13:46,530
Do you remember when
we went to the United States?

146
00:13:48,410 --> 00:13:50,970
It's going to be an adventure,
just like that.

147
00:13:50,990 --> 00:13:52,620
Do they have Disney World there?

148
00:13:56,000 --> 00:13:58,210
Mmm, I don't think so.

149
00:14:13,930 --> 00:14:18,190
Listen to your mother
and your grandmother. All right?

150
00:14:21,230 --> 00:14:24,780
I made more than one reservation so
no one would know what flight you're on.

151
00:14:25,650 --> 00:14:28,670
I spoke to Fernando
and he said it's perfectly legal.

152
00:14:28,700 --> 00:14:32,720
You have every right to leave the country.

153
00:14:32,740 --> 00:14:36,250
- It's like a normal trip.
- A normal trip?

154
00:14:36,870 --> 00:14:38,830
[sighs]

155
00:14:41,500 --> 00:14:42,920
[Pablo] Mmm.

156
00:14:43,840 --> 00:14:48,030
Confess. Do you regret it?

157
00:14:48,050 --> 00:14:50,340
Marrying me, or what?

158
00:14:51,640 --> 00:14:52,680
Not for a second.

159
00:15:04,940 --> 00:15:06,940
[softly]
They may separate us...

160
00:15:09,150 --> 00:15:12,490
but they'll never be able to destroy us.

161
00:15:21,580 --> 00:15:22,880
Go.

162
00:15:33,760 --> 00:15:36,950
[whispers]
The little bunny. The little bunny.

163
00:15:36,970 --> 00:15:39,140
I'll take care of him, all right?

164
00:15:39,980 --> 00:15:41,440
Give me a kiss.

165
00:15:55,330 --> 00:15:57,120
[engine starts]

166
00:16:29,990 --> 00:16:32,030
[sighs]

167
00:16:34,280 --> 00:16:39,040
[Steve] Pablo was right. The government
couldn't stop his family from leaving.

168
00:16:39,660 --> 00:16:43,920
But if you remember, he had
some bad history with Avianca Airlines.

169
00:16:46,670 --> 00:16:49,150
And they made sure as shit
that everybody knew

170
00:16:49,170 --> 00:16:51,630
the Escobars were trying to fly the coop.

171
00:16:54,220 --> 00:16:58,820
[in English] What we know is that Escobar
bought tickets for his family

172
00:16:58,850 --> 00:17:02,330
on eight different outgoing flights
from Bogotá.

173
00:17:02,350 --> 00:17:06,000
Destinations ranging
from Barcelona to Toronto.

174
00:17:06,020 --> 00:17:08,580
Mr. President,
we need to prevent that from happening.

175
00:17:08,610 --> 00:17:12,290
We need to keep the family in play.
If they're allowed to leave Colombia,

176
00:17:12,320 --> 00:17:14,300
we're gonna lose leverage
in the hunt for Escobar.

177
00:17:14,320 --> 00:17:17,800
Legally, there's no way we can stop them
from flying out of the country.

178
00:17:17,820 --> 00:17:19,300
By applying pressure behind the scenes,

179
00:17:19,330 --> 00:17:21,510
we can prevent the family
from being accepted upon arrival.

180
00:17:21,540 --> 00:17:26,140
And if they're kept in Colombia,
he's gonna be worried about their safety.

181
00:17:26,170 --> 00:17:32,360
He'll be more likely to make phone
contact, more likely to... make mistakes.

182
00:17:32,380 --> 00:17:36,680
Because they're more likely
to become victims of Los Pepes.

183
00:17:42,310 --> 00:17:46,750
Mr. President... if the family gets safe
haven, there's no telling what comes next.

184
00:17:46,770 --> 00:17:50,900
Maybe Escobar surrenders,
maybe he goes to war.

185
00:17:51,980 --> 00:17:55,780
The family is leverage. We have to use it.

186
00:18:05,790 --> 00:18:06,790
I agree.

187
00:18:09,500 --> 00:18:13,980
I want one of your people with them
giving us updates, running interference,

188
00:18:14,010 --> 00:18:17,050
and have them find out
where they're going. And stick with them.

189
00:18:18,590 --> 00:18:21,010
[retreating footsteps]

190
00:18:25,100 --> 00:18:26,680
[phone rings]

191
00:18:31,860 --> 00:18:33,540
- Murphy.
- Hey, it's Messina.

192
00:18:33,570 --> 00:18:36,670
I need you to grab your passport
and head to Bogotá International.

193
00:18:36,690 --> 00:18:37,590
Where?

194
00:18:37,610 --> 00:18:41,010
The Escobars are trying to flee the
country. Wherever they go, follow them.

195
00:18:41,030 --> 00:18:44,390
- Yeah. When?
- Now. Once you spot them, check in.

196
00:18:44,410 --> 00:18:47,330
- And Murphy, keep this under wraps.
- Yes, ma'am.

197
00:18:48,290 --> 00:18:49,890
Who was that?

198
00:18:49,920 --> 00:18:51,210
Messina.

199
00:18:53,710 --> 00:18:56,340
- Where you going?
- Going out.

200
00:18:57,090 --> 00:18:59,530
- With your passport?
- Yep.

201
00:18:59,550 --> 00:19:01,720
- Oh, that's all I get?
- Yep.

202
00:19:04,100 --> 00:19:06,770
[indistinct chatter over PA]

203
00:19:12,020 --> 00:19:15,630
- Uh, I'd like to get some tickets, please.
- For... which flight, sir?

204
00:19:15,650 --> 00:19:17,650
Let's see. Madrid, London...

205
00:19:32,000 --> 00:19:34,520
It's Murphy. Get me Messina.

206
00:19:34,540 --> 00:19:38,150
- Messina.
- Hey, it's me. It's the Frankfurt flight.

207
00:19:38,170 --> 00:19:39,880
Germany. Shit.

208
00:19:40,510 --> 00:19:43,990
Yes, Mr. Foreign Minister, but I'm not
talking about some Turkish date farmer

209
00:19:44,010 --> 00:19:47,720
looking to drive a taxi in Berlin.
I'm talking about Pablo Escobar's family.

210
00:19:48,390 --> 00:19:49,600
[sighs]

211
00:19:50,190 --> 00:19:53,710
No. No, they haven't committed any crimes.

212
00:19:53,730 --> 00:19:57,000
[Steve]
Due to events in their fairly recent past,

213
00:19:57,030 --> 00:20:00,650
Germany had some of the softest
immigration standards in Europe.

214
00:20:01,650 --> 00:20:05,130
If you had a pulse,
they tended to let you in.

215
00:20:05,160 --> 00:20:08,100
Now maybe that was good for mankind,

216
00:20:08,120 --> 00:20:11,350
and it was certainly good
for the Escobars.

217
00:20:11,370 --> 00:20:13,480
It was very bad for us.

218
00:20:13,500 --> 00:20:15,540
[opera music plays on radio]

219
00:20:22,130 --> 00:20:25,180
[in Spanish] Sergeant. Private
Hugo Martinez Jr. at your service, sir.

220
00:20:29,270 --> 00:20:30,270
[clears throat]

221
00:20:32,480 --> 00:20:33,810
The colonel's son.

222
00:20:36,860 --> 00:20:38,940
He said you have some
technical background.

223
00:20:40,940 --> 00:20:43,530
I took a couple
of engineering classes, sir.

224
00:20:44,070 --> 00:20:47,200
And I built a ham in my parents' house.

225
00:20:48,240 --> 00:20:52,330
Great. What do you know about RDF?

226
00:20:55,880 --> 00:20:57,290
The basic concept, sir.

227
00:20:58,710 --> 00:21:00,130
The basic concept.

228
00:21:03,970 --> 00:21:05,090
All right.

229
00:21:06,550 --> 00:21:10,030
Get acquainted.
We go out tomorrow afternoon.

230
00:21:10,060 --> 00:21:11,660
And don't worry.

231
00:21:11,680 --> 00:21:15,730
Unlike Carlos Castaño,
this won't hit back.

232
00:21:31,080 --> 00:21:33,930
What's going on?
I'm going to freeze to death out here.

233
00:21:33,960 --> 00:21:35,470
[man]
That's Bogotá. What do you expect?

234
00:21:35,500 --> 00:21:39,900
Hey! What the fuck is wrong with you?
Why are you not working?

235
00:21:39,920 --> 00:21:42,230
Get to work.
I'm not paying you with candy.

236
00:21:42,260 --> 00:21:44,980
- Okay, okay.
- [Blackie] Pass me the phone, boy.

237
00:21:45,010 --> 00:21:48,700
Make some fucking bombs.
You need an invitation to start working?

238
00:21:48,720 --> 00:21:53,660
- [men murmur indistinctly]
- Hurry, boy! You get to work too!

239
00:21:53,680 --> 00:21:55,700
And don't smoke near the gunpowder.

240
00:21:55,730 --> 00:21:56,790
[grumbles]

